06562nam a22013455i 9781400887828DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008878287 a10.1515/97814008878282doi  a(DE-B1597)487942  a(OCoLC)988759272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJN96.A58 7aPOL0050002bisacsh04a320.9472231 aPop-Eleches, Grigore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommunism's Shadow :bHistorical Legacies and Contemporary Political Attitudes /cGrigore Pop-Eleches, Joshua Tucker. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b25 line illus. 25 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Political Behavior ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCountry Code Abbreviations Used in Figures 4.1, 5.1, 6.1, and 7.1 -- tChapter 1. Communism's Shadow -- tChapter 2. Living through Communism -- tChapter 3. Methods and Data -- tChapter 4. Democracy -- tChapter 5. Markets -- tChapter 6. Social Welfare -- tChapter 7. Gender Equality -- tChapter 8. Temporal Resilience and Change -- tChapter 9. Legacies and Communism -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has long been assumed that the historical legacy of Soviet Communism would have an important effect on post-communist states. However, prior research has focused primarily on the institutional legacy of communism. Communism's Shadow instead turns the focus to the individuals who inhabit post-communist countries, presenting a rigorous assessment of the legacy of communism on political attitudes.Post-communist citizens hold political, economic, and social opinions that consistently differ from individuals in other countries. Grigore Pop-Eleches and Joshua Tucker introduce two distinct frameworks to explain these differences, the first of which focuses on the effects of living in a post-communist country, and the second on living through communism. Drawing on large-scale research encompassing post-communist states and other countries around the globe, the authors demonstrate that living through communism has a clear, consistent influence on why citizens in post-communist countries are, on average, less supportive of democracy and markets and more supportive of state-provided social welfare. The longer citizens have lived through communism, especially as adults, the greater their support for beliefs associated with communist ideology-the one exception being opinions regarding gender equality.A thorough and nuanced examination of communist legacies' lasting influence on public opinion, Communism's Shadow highlights the ways in which political beliefs can outlast institutional regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPost-communismzEurope, Eastern. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  aLeninist regimes.  aSoviet Communism.  aSoviet Union.  aSoviet communism.  aadult communist exposure.  aaggregate-level data.  aanalyses.  aanti-democratic attitudes.  aattitudinal change.  aattitudinal convergence.  aattitudinal differences.  achildhood communist exposure.  acommunism.  acommunist education.  acommunist ideology.  acommunist legacies.  acommunist message.  acommunist regime.  acommunist regimes.  acommunist rhetoric.  acommunist socialization effects.  acommunist socialization project.  ademocracy.  ademocratic deficit.  ademocratic support.  ademocratic values.  adevelopmental differences.  aeconomic performance.  aeconomic principles.  aexposure.  afleeting legacies.  agender equality.  a